05404nam a22007935i 9781501735554DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018052346  a97815017355547 a10.7591/97815017355542doi  a(DE-B1597)527439  a(OCoLC)1061862602  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aDS889.5 4aDS889.5b.Y455 2019 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a940.5352231 aYellen, Jeremy A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere :bWhen Total Empire Met Total War /cJeremy A. Yellen. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (306 p.) :b9 b&w halftones, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Names, Transliterations, and Translations -- tIntroduction. WHEN TOTAL EMPIRE MET TOTAL WAR -- tPart I. THE IMAGINED SPHERE -- t1. INTO THE TIGER’S DEN -- t2. ORDER BEGETS WAR -- t3. IMAGINING CO-PROSPERITY -- tPart II. THE CONTESTED SPHERE -- t4. THE PATRIOTIC COLLABORATORS -- t5. A NEW DEAL FOR GREATER EAST ASIA? -- t6. INDEPENDENCE IN TRANSITION -- tConclusion. THE CO-PROSPERITY SPHERE IN HISTORY -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere, Jeremy Yellen exposes the history, politics, and intrigue that characterized the era when Japan's "total empire" met the total war of World War II. He illuminates the ways in which the imperial center and its individual colonies understood the concept of the Sphere, offering two sometimes competing, sometimes complementary, and always intertwined visions—one from Japan, the other from Burma and the Philippines.Yellen argues that, from 1940 to 1945, the Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere epitomized two concurrent wars for Asia's future: the first was for a new type of empire in Asia, and the second was a political war, waged by nationalist elites in the colonial capitals of Rangoon and Manila. Exploring Japanese visions for international order in the face of an ever-changing geopolitical situation, The Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere explores wartime Japan's desire to shape and control its imperial future while its colonies attempted to do the same. At Japan's zenith as an imperial power, the Sphere represented a plan for regional domination; by the end of the war, it had been recast as the epitome of cooperative internationalism. In the end, the Sphere could not survive wartime defeat, and Yellen's lucidly written account reveals much about the desires of Japan as an imperial and colonial power, as well as the ways in which the subdued colonies in Burma and the Philippines jockeyed for agency and a say in the future of the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  aWorld War II, WWII, colonialism, international order, Southeast Asia, Asian, Japan, Burma, Philippines, military history, Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere, Japanese, Asia, Empire, fascism, imperialism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z